2. Explain the instructions to the participant:
    1. Ask the participant to keep the gaze on the central fixation cross for the entire duration of the activity;
    2. Instruct the participant to answer by pressing the spacebar whenever they perceive gray circles within the checkerboard;
    3. Instruct the participant to withhold the response whenever they perceive an empty checkerboard;
    4. Provide the participant with a sample of the stimuli that will be presented;
    5. Ask the participant to place the right hand in the position to promptly press the spacebar.
3. Make sure the instructions are clear to the participant and clarify any questions.
4. Make sure that the participant is in a comfortable position.
5. Check the distance between the participant’s eyes and the screen (57 cm) at the beginning of each block.
6. Make the room light dimmed.
7. Run the task.
8. Cap placement:
    1. Center the cap at the sagittal plane using the distance between the inion (the bony protrusion at the back of the skull) and nasion (the bony ridge between the eyebrows);
    2. Center the cap at the coronal plane using the distance between the ears.
9. Reducing electrode impedance:
    1. Skin preparation: clean the skin at the electrode-skin contact by scrubbing with alcohol and a cotton swab;
    2. Apply and distribute the electrode gel with a cotton swab until desired impedance is reached for all of the electrodes (ground, reference and EOG electrodes: < 5 kΩ; remaining electrodes: < 10 kΩ);
    3. Visually inspect the signal for any other obvious but otherwise undetected problem in the EEG signal.
10. Insert the E-prime output scores containing the participant behavioral performance in the prepared scoring sheet.
11. Estimate the individual performance for each iso-luminant contrast taking into account also the false alarm rate to calculate a sigmoid function:
    1. Calculate accuracy percentage separately for each contrast and for the left and right stimulus trials by dividing the number of correct responses for the total number of stimuli with that contrast and multiplying it by 100;
    2. Calculate false alarms percentage separately for the left and right stimulus trials, dividing the number of false alarms for the total number of catch stimuli of that hemifield and multiplying it by 100;
    3. Create one column for each side containing the percentage of false alarms changing its number sign in negative and the accuracy percentages.
